===Etymology===
1580, from {{etyl|frm}} {{term|massacre|lang=frm}}, from {{etyl|fro}} {{term|macacre|macacre, macecle|slaughterhouse, butchery|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|ML.}} {{term|mazacrium|lang=la}} "massacre, slaughter, killing", also "the head of a newly killed stag", of {{etyl|gem}} origin, from {{etyl|nds}} *{{term||matskelen|lang=nds}} "to massacre" (compare {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|metzeln|metzeln||lang=de}} "to massacre"), frequentive of {{term|matsken|matsken, matzgen|to cut, hew|lang=de}}, from {{proto|gem-pro|maitanan|to cut|lang=en}}, from {{proto|ine-pro|mei-|small|lang=en}}. Akin to {{etyl|goh|-}} {{term|meizan||to cut|lang=goh}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|matsen|matsen|to maul, kill|lang=nl}}, dialectal {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|metzgern|lang=de}} "to butcher, kill", {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|metzgen||to cut, kill, slaughter cattle|lang=de}}, {{term|Metzger||a butcher|lang=de}}, {{term|Metzelei|Metzelei|massacre|lang=de}}, {{etyl|got|-}} {{term|𐌼𐌰𐌹𐍄𐌰𐌽||to cut|tr=maitan|lang=got|sc=Goth}}. See also French {{term|massacrer|lang=fr}}.

